@Node "Intro" "CheckStart.guide/Intro"
@Toc "Main"

What is it?
^^^^^^^^^^^

Well, it is a small utility which should be used at boot-up. It checks the time, and if it is within
given limits, starts a script of your choice. The idea came from a sysop who wanted his BBS to start
on every boot up, but only if the time was within his opening times. It can of course also be used for
other programs aswell.

You might say: "Why the hell can't I just add the program to my startup-sequence?". Well, let's say
that you run a BBS and you want to play a game that requires a lot of memory, you would have to either
close the program after boot up, or you could remove the line from your startup-sequence. Both ways
are slow and akward.

If are using CheckStart, you could enable the 'Last chance' ...and if you press a button before 3 seconds
has passed, the program will not start.



@EndNode

@Node "req" "CheckStart.guide/req"
@Toc "Main"

What does it require?
^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^

It should run on every Amiga configuration, but you need WB2.0 to use the interface.

You will also need the Arexx programming language.

The XEN.font is required for the interface, this font comes from the MagicWB package.
@EndNode

@Node "con" "CheckStart.guide/req"
@Toc "Main"

Configuring the bastard...
^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^

There are two possibilities; namely interface and config file editing.

The quick and dirty way is to use an editor to change the config file (CheckStart.config), just load
it into your editor and change the options.

You could also use the interface, it is easier, and probably better for beginners.

@EndNode

@Node "opt" "CheckStart.guide/opt"
@Toc "Main"

The options...
^^^^^^^^^^^^^^

If you are editing the config file, you will se the following:

----------------------------------------------------------------file begin--------------

/********************************************/
/*  CheckStart v1.0 © Michael Barkholt 1996 */
/*                                          */
/*              Interface:YES               */
/*              Between:1800                */
/*                and:2359                  */
/*                                          */
/*         Optional between:0000            */
/*                and:0800                  */
/*               Disable:NO                 */
/*              Last chance:NO              */
/********************************************/

address command

Execute 'work:cd-rom

----------------------------------------------------------------file end----------------

Ok, let us start from the top:

---------------------
INTERFACE: YES/NO 
---------------------
                   
This option determins whether interface should be ON or OFF. If this option has been set to
OFF, the interface will never reveal itself, thus making the program almost invisible (no
interface visible to the user - CheckStart just does what you told it to do).

If set to ON, the interface will open no matter if a script is launched or not.
 
---------------------
BETWEEN:xxxx
AND:xxxx
---------------------

This is where you specify a range of time. If the current time is between the two given times, the
script will be executed. The format is HHMM, i.e. half past six is 1830. You must remember that the
two times given MUST be in the same day! If you want the time range to spread over more than a day, 
you have to use the OPTIONAL time range.

---------------------
OPTIONAL BETWEEN:xxxx
AND:xxxx
---------------------

Here you can enter another time range, it is best used in conjunction with the first range, i.e. if a
BBS is open from 19:00 one day to 07:00 the next, you should set the range to 00:00 -> 07:00

---------------------
DISABLE: YES/NO
---------------------

This is very easy to understand. 'YES' will disable the entire program, 'NO' will make sure it runs.

---------------------
LAST CHANCE: YES/NO
---------------------

If YES, a small bar will appear giving you 3-4 seconds to press the close gadget, and thus avoid 
executing the script.

---------------------
EXECUTE:
---------------------

This in the Arexx command which launches the script. The argument is execute '<path>' - just write
the path.


Using the interface...
^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^

The interface is pretty easy to use; just write the time in the boxes and use the 'CD' button to
find a script. - Remember to save before quitting!!! NOTE - make sure that there are no " ' " around the
path before saving! I.e. work:start.script - and not - 'work:start.script'. Get the picture...?


Known problems...
^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^

The CheckBoxes will not show the options stated in the config file. I.e. the Last Chance
option has 'YES' in it in the config file - the box in the interface remains unchecked. Just
remember to check it before saving.



@EndNode

